        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity estimate:
We base our exposure time estimate on the CO 3-2 fluxes for star-forming galaxies with similar redshifts and SFRs in the sample of Tacconi et al. (2013) and Saintongel et al. (2013, correcting the fluxes for the lensing magnification). Based on these samples we estimate that a flux of 0.1 Jy km/s is a sensible target flux limit. Some galaxies, e.g. cB58, are significantly fainter than this where as other with the same SFR are brighter than this.

The objective is to detect at 5 sigma a CO 3-2 emission line at z=2.583 with a flux of 0.10 Jy km/s and a velocity width of 250 km/s FWHM (as measured from the optical [OIII] emission line). We do not expect any continuum. The redshifted line fall at 96.5 GHz in band 3. 

We request one baseband in FDM mode with a spectral averaging to provide an instrumental velocity resolution of ~25 km/s. We will further be able to smooth the velocity resolution to ~100 km/s, which is how we base our sensitivity request.

Configuration and angular resolution:
For this experiment we are just interested in detecting the line and therefore we will ask for a  configuration that maximizes the signal-to-noise ratio for detection while at the same time allowing us to determine the centroid of the emission more precisely than the distance between the QSO and the absorbing galaxy, hence 2 arcsec is sufficient. 

Q0918+1636 is not detected in the NVSS 1.4 GHz survey, and so has a flux density lower than about 1.5 mJy at 1.4 GHz. It therefore should not have much continuum at 3 mm.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
