    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Imaging and absorption studies of galaxies at z&gt;2 provide complementary information. In particular Damped Lyman-alpha Absorbers (DLAs) provide very detailed information about chemical abundances. For about a dozen z&gt;2 DLAs the absorbing galaxy has been identified providing what can be considered Rosetta stones for combining imaging and absorption studies of z&gt;2 galaxies. Our objective here is to image the distribution of CO molecules around the most spectacular of these namely the z=2.583 DLA galaxy towards the z=3 QSO Q0918+1636. The galaxy counterpart of the DLA is a strongly star-forming galaxy located 2.0 arcsec from the QSO line-of-sight. The DLA absorber, probing gas 16 kpc from the centre of the absorbing galaxy, has solar metallicity and contains molecular hydrogen and dust. The aim of this ALMA proposal is to detet CO (3-2) using band 3. If succesfull we will later apply for time to map the distribution of CO 3-2 in order to better understand the relation between the galaxy detected in emission and the absorption probed by the QSO.   </prp:abstract>
